“After we’ve had an opportunity to collect what evidence is available where the event happened and talk to the people who can tell us anything they know about what happened and get the reports from the medical examiner, we turn now to looking back. Was there anything that indicated that something could have been happening to prevent this that police could have been a part of, should have been a part of?”Glavin said the investigation is not closed by any means.“It’s not open because we don’t know what occurred; it’s open because we want to understand what occurred better,” he said.He said it was a “very tough” scene for investigators, but added it is their professional duty to work the case and provide answers for the family and community.The boys played with the Spruce Grove Minor Hockey Association, whose president posted a statement online calling the deaths an “unimaginable tragedy.”They were both students at the nearby Greystone Centennial Middle School, who have activated a trauma team to help students cope with the tragedy.A vigil for the boys was held Tuesday in Whitecourt.
